PRESIDENT Jacob Zuma yesterday said he was saddened to learn of the death of Riot Mkhwanazi (81).Mkhwanazi was a political activist and recipient of the Order of Mendi for Bravery. The president rewarded Mkhwanazi for his contribution to the liberation struggle in 2014. &ldquo;We have lost a disciplined veteran and a true revolutionary who sacrificed his youth and risked his life for the liberation of South Africa. We wish to convey our deepest condolences to the Mkhwanazi family. May his soul rest in peace.&rdquo;Mkhwanazi was arrested with Zuma when they were crossing the South African border into Botswana in 1963.They were sentenced to 10 years imprisonment on Robben Island. This where Mkhwanazi learned to read and write.The presidency said: &ldquo;Soon before his release in 1974, Mkhwanazi and other prisoners due for release received a letter from Nelson Mandela urging them to continue the struggle where they had left off before their arrest and imprisonment. &ldquo;After his release, Mkhwanazi was banned. He later went into exile and spent many years in Mozambique. He returned to South Africa in the early 1990s.&rdquo;